Formation of a sinus tract often indicates lingering pathogenic toxins.
The liver pertains to wood, and the heart pertains to fire.
The spleen pertains to earth, and the lungs pertain to metal.
The kidneys pertain to water.
The liver governs ascending and effusion, while the lungs govern purification and descent.
The spleen governs ascending the clear, while the stomach governs descending the turbid.
Heart fire warms Yang-Qi throughout the body.
Kidney water nourishes Yin fluid throughout the body.
Free unfolding of liver wood helps Qi movement remain smooth.
Purification and descent of lung metal help regulate the water pathways.
Proper movement of spleen earth helps generate essence.
Qi is the commander of blood.
Blood is the mother of Qi.
When Qi moves, blood moves.
When Qi stagnates, blood becomes static.
Blood desertion can lead to Qi desertion.
Sufficient body fluids maintain the moistness of the skin.
Deficiency of body fluids can make the striae dry.
Lung-Qi disperses body fluids to the skin and hair.
Spleen-Qi transports the essence of food and drink.
Kidney-Qi steams and transforms body fluids.
The triple Jiao regulates the water pathways to move body fluids.
